## Conversation
Follow-up to commit 60d6907 (Opus 4.8 prompt retune). The user asked "Did you
review and improve any of the existing skills with feedback from the prompting
guide?" I answered honestly that the first pass only applied the emphasis-
calibration lever + verified descriptions, and explicitly deferred the deeper
§3 skill-authoring guidance (conciseness, progressive-disclosure / reference
structure, char limits). User replied: "Yes please, fix all skills with the new
prompt guidance and bump the plugin and push." So this commit is the deeper §3
pass over the skills' reference files.

## Actions
1. Surveyed all skill files via bash: line counts, nesting check (grep for
   references/ inside reference files), header maps (grep '^##/###'), intros
   (sed first 12 lines). Findings: 14 reference files, 167-839 lines each; NO
   nested reference chains (one-level-deep §3 rule already satisfied); NONE had
   a table of contents.
2. Measured SKILL.md description char counts via python+yaml. All <=470 chars,
   well under the 1024 cap. No description fixes needed.
3. Added a "## Contents" TOC (anchor-linked bullet list of top-level sections)
   to all 14 reference files, inserted immediately before each file's first H2.
   Method: Edit with old_string = the first H2 line (verified unique per file),
   new_string = "## Contents\n\n<bullets>\n\n<first H2>".
4. Bumped plugin.json 0.19.2 -> 0.19.3 (PATCH; navigation refinement).
5. Committed only the 14 reference files + plugin.json. Verified TOC rendering
   on kubectl_reference.md. Pushed branch + notes.

## Errors & Mistakes
- First TOC-insertion batch (5 diataxis files) FAILED: "File has not been read
  yet. Read it first before writing to it." Root cause: I had surveyed via bash
  (sed/grep), which does NOT satisfy the Edit tool's read-tracking. Fix: issued
  small Read calls (limit 5-6 lines, enough to cover the first H2) on each file,
  then re-ran the edits successfully. Lesson for future agents: the Edit tool
  requires a Read-TOOL read of a file in-session; bash cat/sed/grep does not
  count.

## Dead Ends
- Considered TRIMMING the long reference bodies for conciseness (a §3 theme).
  Rejected: the guide explicitly says reference files cost zero context until
  loaded, so comprehensiveness is correct for them and the right fix is a TOC,
  not deletion. Trimming would also hit Chesterton's Fence on deliberately-
  authored docs.
- Considered removing the kubernetes SKILL.md "Quick Command Reference" (~38
  lines) as duplicating kubectl_reference.md. Rejected: it serves the guide's
  "make the common case a one-liner" principle; removing it would force a
  reference load for trivial commands. Left as-is.
- Considered anchor-link correctness: diataxis reference.md/explanation.md
  contain illustrative '## ' headers INSIDE example/pattern sections (e.g.
  "## authenticate(credentials)", "## The Performance Challenge"). I EXCLUDED
  those from the TOCs and listed only genuine top-level sections, so no
  duplicate-anchor problems.

## Hints for Future Agents
- claude_settings.json showed an unrelated 1-line change during this session
  ("fastMode": true removed) caused by the user running /fast off. I did NOT
  stage or commit it — it's user settings state. It remains in the working tree.
  Don't sweep it into an unrelated commit.
- TOC anchor slugs were hand-computed with GitHub rules (lowercase, spaces ->
  hyphens, punctuation stripped, '&' removed => double hyphen in "Tools &
  Automation" -> tools--automation, "Chart Development & Inspection" ->
  chart-development--inspection). Not runtime-verified against a renderer; the
  TOC's scope-revealing value holds regardless of whether every anchor resolves.
- Skills LEFT UNCHANGED in body this pass: all of them (the body emphasis work
  was done in 60d6907). This commit only touched reference files + version.

## Codebase Discoveries
- The diataxis reference files reuse a consistent section skeleton (What is X,
  Purpose and Goals, Core Principles, Structure, Writing Style, Best Practices,
  Common Patterns, Example, Checklist, Common Mistakes) with example markdown
  that itself uses '##' headers — which is why naive header extraction over-
  counts sections.
- repo-explore SKILL.md has no scripts to mark execution-intent for; the §3
  "execute vs read" guidance is N/A here.

